Nelson Mandela Metropolitan University (NMMU) on Tuesday celebrated the inauguration of Professor Sibongile Muthwa as Vice-Chancellor and Dr Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi as Chancellor They join NMMU Chair of Council, former Ambassador Nozipho January-Bardill. “I am honoured to form part of this trio of women,” said Fraser-Moleketi at the ceremony. She said NMMU was the only university to have three women at its helm, according to the university’s Facebook page. Fraser-Moleketi added that she was “deeply humbled” by the confidence the council and university community had in her. In her acceptance speech, she paid tribute to many prominent leaders, including the late Winnie Madikizela-Mandela and ANC veteran Zola Skweyiya, who she said were her former colleagues. The university announced Fraser-Moleketi, a former Minister of Public Service and Administration, as its new Chancellor last month. READ MORE: More violence and arrests at Wits, NMMU She was awarded an honorary doctorate at the institution last year for her contribution to leadership in social and economic transformation, with specific emphasis on the empowerment of women. Muthwa assumed her position on 1 January. From 2010-2017, she was the Deputy Vice-Chancellor for institutional support at NMMU. Before that, she served as Director-General in the Eastern Cape government. In 2014, Muthwa was appointed as a Commissioner of the Financial and Fiscal Commission, and in July 2017, she was appointed as its Deputy Chairperson. – News24